The US Supreme Court recently heard arguments on the death penalty for criminals aged under 18, focusing on the case of Christopher Simmons.
Advocates argue against executing juveniles, citing evolving standards of decency and a global consensus against it.
Justices debated whether young offenders truly understand the consequences of their actions.
International pressure mounts to end the practice, with only a few countries still allowing it.
The court faces a crucial decision on whether to limit capital punishment to those legally adults.
The case has sparked global attention and raised questions about evolving societal norms regarding juvenile offenders.
